04009nam a22006735i 9781442685628DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192007onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426856287 a10.3138/97814426856282doi  a(DE-B1597)497064  a(OCoLC)1083582898  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a306.709182/109041 aRutherford, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWorld Made Sexy :bFreud to Madonna /cPaul Rutherford. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Exhibiting Eros -- t2. Liberation Theory -- t3. The Erotic Sell -- t4. Signs of Angst -- t5. The Erotics of Power -- t6. A Theatre of the Libido -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tResearch Sources and Sites -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe cult of eroticism is a pervasive force in modern society, affecting almost every aspect of our daily lives. In this book, Paul Rutherford argues that this phenomenon is a product of one of the major commercial and political enterprises of the twentieth and twenty-first centuries: the creation of desire - for sex, for wealth, and for entertainment.A World Made Sexy examines museum exhibitions, art, books, magazines, films, and television to explore the popular rise of eroticism in America and across the developed world. Starting with a brief foray into the history of pornography, Rutherford goes on to explore a sexual liberation movement shaped by the ideas of Marx and Freud, the erotic styles of Salvador Dali and pop art, the pioneering use of publicity as erotica by Playboy and other media, and the growing concerns of cultural critics over the emergence of a regime of stimulation. In one case study, Rutherford pairs James Bond and Madonna in order to examine the link between sex and aggression. He details how television advertising after 1980 constructed a theatre of the libido to entice the buying public, and concludes by situating the cultivation of eroticism in the wider context of Michel Foucault's views on social power and governmentality, and specifically how they relate to sexuality, during the modern era.A World Made Sexy is about power and pleasure, emancipation and domination, and the relationship between the personal passions and social controls that have crafted desire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEroticaxHistory. 0aSex in advertisingxHistory. 0aSex in mass mediaxHistory. 0aSex in popular culturexHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268562840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442685628423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442685628.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK